'''Debian''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|d|ɛ|b|i|ə|n}}) is an [[operating system]] composed of [[free and open source software|free]] software mostly carrying the [[GNU General Public License]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.debian.org/intro/free | title = What Does Free Mean? or What do you mean by Free Software? | publisher = The Debian Project | work = official Debian site | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref> The operating system is developed by an internet collaboration of volunteers aligned with ''The Debian Project''.

Debian systems can use either the [[Linux kernel]] (known as the ''Debian GNU/Linux'' distribution), the [[FreeBSD]] kernel (known as the ''[[Debian GNU/kFreeBSD]]'' distribution) or, more recently, the [[GNU Hurd]] kernel (more precisely, the [[GNU Mach]] [[microkernel]] and its servers; known as the ''[[Debian GNU/Hurd]]'' distribution).<ref name="About Debian">{{cite web | url = http://www.debian.org/intro/about | title = About Debian | publisher = The Debian Project | work = official Debian site}}</ref>

Debian GNU/Linux is one of the most popular [[Linux distribution]]s for personal and Internet [[Server (computing)|server]] machines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/247845/debian_linux_named_most_popular_distro_for_web_servers.html|title=Debian Linux Named Most Popular Distro for Web Servers|author=Katherine Noyes|publisher=[[PC World]]|date=2012-01-11|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/why-debian-matters-more-than-ever|title=Why Debian matters more than ever|author=Joe Brockmeier|publisher=[[Network World]]|date=2011-07-02|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-mag.com/id/7651/|title=The Five Distros That Changed Linux|author=Steven J. Vaughan-Nichols|publisher=[[Linux Magazine]]|date=2009-12-16|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://w3techs.com/technologies/details/os-linux/all/all | title = Usage Statistics and Market Share of Linux for Websites, October 2012 | publisher = W3Techs.com | accessdate=2012-10-13}}</ref> Debian is seen as a solid Linux, and as a consequence has been used as a base for other Linux distributions; Distrowatch lists 144 active Debian derivatives.<ref>[http://distrowatch.com/search.php?ostype=All&category=All&origin=All&basedon=Debian&notbasedon=None&desktop=All&architecture=All&status=Active Based on Debian, status active] Distrowatch</ref><ref>[https://wiki.debian.org/Derivatives Debian Derivatives] Debian wiki</ref> Debian has been [[Fork (software development)|forked]] many times, but is not affiliated with [[Debian family|its derivatives]].

The vital role the Debian project plays in free software is demonstrated by its advancement of development and security patches relating to its strong participation in [[Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures|CVE]] compatibility efforts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Debian and CVE compatibility|url=http://www.debian.org/security/cve-compatibility|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>

== Features ==
The Debian project released a new kernel as of Wheezy's release date: the Debian GNU/kFreeBSD kernel. Debian now supports two kernels, [[Linux]] and [[Debian GNU/kFreeBSD|kFreeBSD]], and offers other kernels as development works (GNU Hurd and NetBSD). This project's new kernel has recently come out of preview but still lacks the amount of software available as on Debian's Linux. The kernel is offered for Intel/AMD 32-bit and 64-bit architecture machines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Release Notes for Debian 7.0 (wheezy), 64-bit PC|url=http://www.debian.org/releases/wheezy/amd64/release-notes/|publisher=debian.org|accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref> Wheezy is officially supported on ten machine architectures and also brought support for two new architectures: s390x and armhf.

Debian is still primarily known as a [[Linux distribution]] with access to online repositories hosting over 37,500 software packages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Debian|url=http://www.debian.org/|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> Debian officially hosts ''free'' software on its repositories but also allows non-free software to be installed. Debian includes popular programs such as [[LibreOffice]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.debian.org/News/2011/20110623 | title=Debian Moves to LibreOffice | publisher=Debian |accessdate=2012-03-05}}</ref> [[Mozilla Corporation software rebranded by the Debian project|Iceweasel]] (a [[rebranding]] of [[Firefox]]), [[Evolution (software)|Evolution]] mail, CD/DVD writing programs, music and video players, image viewers and editors, and [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] viewers. The cost of developing all the packages included in Debian 5.0 ''lenny'' (323 million lines of code) using the [[COCOMO]] model, has been estimated to be about [[United States dollar|US$]] 8 billion.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate =2011-02-28 | url =http://gsyc.es/~frivas/paper.pdf | title =Measuring Lenny: the size of Debian 5.0 | publisher =libresoft}}{{dead link|date=July 2013}}</ref> [[Ohloh]] estimates that the [[codebase]] (68 million lines of code) using the same model, would cost about [[United States dollar|US$]] 1.2 billion to develop.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate =2013-07-03 | url =http://www.ohloh.net/p/debian| title =Debian GNU/Linux | publisher =Ohloh.net}}</ref>

Debian offers 10 DVD and 69 CD images for download and installation, but only the first optical [[ISO image|iso]] image of any of its downloadable sets is sufficient. Debian requires the first installable image, but uses online repositories for additional software. Debian's basic installation requires only the first CD or DVD of its release in order to have a working desktop experience. The Wheezy release offers to install a variety of default Desktops from its DVD boot menu ([[GNOME]], [[KDE]], [[Xfce]], and [[LXDE]]) and allows visually-impaired people to use its installer. The new feature in Debian's latest installer of Wheezy for the visually-impaired supports a mode which is textual but performs audio output for each stage of installation. Debian offers different network installation methods for expert users. A minimal install of Debian is available via the 'netinstall' CD, whereby Debian is installed with just a base and later additional software can be downloaded from the internet.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.debian.org/distrib/netinst | title=Installing Debian GNU/Linux via the Internet | publisher=Debian | accessdate=2008-12-11}}</ref>

Debian's new form of installation-from-USB has been supported since its sixth edition. Debian supports this capability inside its first iso-file of any of its install media sets (whether CD or DVD) and does not require the help of 'extraction tools' such as [[unetbootin]]. This new feature is called [[ISO image|Hybrid iso]] in which an .iso file is dumped to USB. Debian is one of the few Linux distributions offering this feature with its install iso media, and other distributions are starting to adopt alike.

Other notable new features in Debian's latest release include: Multiarch, which allows 32-bit Linux software to run on 64-bit operating system installs;<ref>{{cite web|title=Multiarch, The Case For Multiarch|url=http://wiki.debian.org/Multiarch/TheCaseForMultiarch|publisher=Debian community|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> improved multimedia support, reducing reliance on third-party repositories; compiled packages with hardened security flags; [[AppArmor]], which can protect a system against unknown vulnerabilities; and [[systemd]], which shipped as a technology preview.

Debian's install-media is distributed via downloadable CD/DVD [[ISO image|images]] from its mirrored sites,<ref>{{cite web|title=Debian worldwide mirror sites|url=http://www.debian.org/mirror/list|publisher=debian.org|accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]], [[jigdo]] and from optional retailers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.debian.org/CD/ | title=Debian GNU/Linux on CDs | publisher=Debian | accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref>

=== Desktop environments ===
Debian offers ''stable'' and ''testing'' CD images specifically built for [[GNOME]] (the default), [[KDE Plasma Workspaces]], [[Xfce]] and [[LXDE]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.debian.org/News/2007/20070408 | title = Debian GNU/Linux 4.0 released | publisher = Debian | date = 2008-04-08 | accessdate = 2008-10-31}}</ref> Less common [[window manager]]s such as [[Enlightenment (window manager)|Enlightenment]], [[Openbox]], [[Fluxbox]], [[GNUstep]], [[IceWM]], [[Window Maker]] and others can also be installed. It was previously suggested that the default desktop environment of version 7.0 "Wheezy" may be switched to [[Xfce]], because GNOME 3 might not fit on the first CD of the set.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=MTE1NTk | author = Michael Larabel | title = Debian Now Defaults To Xfce Desktop | publisher = Phoronix Media | date = 2012-08-08 | accessdate = 2012-08-27}}</ref> The Debian Installer team announced that the first CD includes GNOME thanks to their efforts to minimize the amount of disc space GNOME takes up.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel-announce/2012/10/msg00007.html | title = Debian Installer 7.0 Beta3 release}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2012/09/msg00254.html | title = Re: CD1 without a network mirror isn't sufficient to install a full desktop environment}}</ref> In November 2013 it was announced that the desktop environment of version 8.0 "Jessie" would change to Xfce. Demand for Xfce will be evaluated and the default environment may switch back to GNOME again just before Jessie is frozen.<ref>http://anonscm.debian.org/gitweb/?p=tasksel/tasksel.git;a=commitdiff;h=dfca406eb694e0ac00ea04b12fc912237e01c9b5</ref><ref>http://news.softpedia.com/news/Debian-8-0-quot-Jessie-quot-Ditches-GNOME-and-Adopts-Xfce-397262.shtml</ref>

[[MATE (desktop environment)|MATE]] and [[Cinnamon (user interface)|Cinnamon]] are not available in the official Debian package repositories.

=== Blends ===
A concept similar to Fedora spins is Debian blends.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}

=== Debian-Live ===
A Debian-Live system is officially supported by the Debian project. A Debian-Live system can be booted from [[removable media]] (CDs, DVDs, USB thumb drive), and possibly from netboot images.<ref>{{cite web|title=Live install images|url=http://www.debian.org/CD/live/|publisher=debian.org|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> Debian-Live allows a user to try a Debian desktop without actually installing it but with the penalty of no persistent storage and it would be running with degraded speed. Debian-Live comes tailored and made available as a variety of community ''prebuilds'', such as [[GNOME]], [[KDE Plasma Workspaces]], [[Xfce]], [[LXDE]], and [[rescue]] boot [[Desktop environment|environments]]. An option for permanently installing Debian on a [[hard disk]] is also made available from these boot environments. Personalized Debian-Live images can be built with the live-build tool,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://live.debian.net/devel/live-build/ | title = DebianLive/ live-build: Debian Wiki | publisher = Debian | accessdate = 2011-08-15}}</ref> in which images are generated for CD/DVD/USB drives and for netboot purposes. Live-magic is another tool used for personalizing Debian-Live images, along with the assistance of a [[Graphical user interface|graphical interface]].

The official ''standard'' Debian-live images are available only for the i386 and amd64 related architectures as indicated from the website http://www.debian.org/CD/live/

=== {{anchor|EMBEDDED}}Embedded systems ===
Recent releases of Debian support an increasing number of [[ARM architecture|ARM]]-based [[network-attached storage|NAS]] devices. The cheap [[NSLU2]] was supported by Debian 4.0 and 5.0<ref>{{cite web|url=http://linuxgazette.net/161/brownss.html |title=Upgrading your Slug LG #161 |publisher=Linuxgazette.net |date= |accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref> and can be upgraded to Debian 6.0 although there are problems with a 6.0 clean install.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyrius.com/debian/nslu2/install.html |title=Installing Debian on NSLU2 |publisher=Cyrius.com |date=2011-02-24 |accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref> Debian 5.0 added support for the [[Buffalo network-attached storage series|Buffalo]] Kurobox Pro,<ref name="debian.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.debian.org/releases/lenny/arm/release-notes/ch-whats-new.en.html#newforarm |title=Chapter 2. What's new in Debian GNU/Linux 5.0 |publisher=Debian.org |date= |accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref> and Debian 6.0 for the [[SheevaPlug]].<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=http://www.debian.org/releases/squeeze/armel/release-notes/ch-whats-new.en.html#newforarm |title=Chapter 2. What's new in Debian GNU/Linux 6.0 |publisher=Debian.org |date= |accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref>

Other NAS devices supported by Debian, but perhaps not so widely used by home users, include GLAN Tank<ref>The GLAN Tank is a Japanese NAS device, described on Japanese Wikipedia [[:ja:GLAN Tank|GLAN Tank]] {{ja icon}}</ref> and Thecus N2100 as of Debian 4.0,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debian.org/releases/etch/arm/release-notes/ch-whats-new.en.html |work=Release Notes for Debian GNU/Linux 4.0 ("etch"), ARM | title = What's new in Debian GNU/Linux 4.0 |publisher=Debian.org |date=2007-08-16 |accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref> QNAP Turbo Station (TS-109, TS-209, TS-409) and HP mv2120 as of Debian 5.0,<ref name="debian.org"/> and QNAP Turbo NAS TS-11x, TS-21x and TS-41x, OpenRD, Lanner EM7210 and Intel SS4000-e as of Debian 6.0.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

==== Emdebian Grip ====
The ''Emdebian Grip'' project &mdash; a small Debian-compatible installation &mdash; provides a more fine-grained control over package selection, size, dependencies and content, in order to enable creation of small and efficient Debian packages for use on resource-limited [[embedded system]]s.  Reduced installation size is one of the main benefits coming from the Emdebian Grip.<ref>{{cite web
 | url = http://www.emdebian.org/grip/
 | title = Emdebian Grip packages: A smaller Debian-compatible distro
 | accessdate = 2013-10-16
 | publisher = emdebian.org
}}</ref>

Emdebian Grip maintains as much compatibility as possible with Debian.  In essence, Emdebian Grip re-packs the <code>.deb</code> archives from Debian while removing unneeded files, such as manpages, info documents, documentation and unwanted translation files.  In other words, Emdebian Grip is a Debian distribution builder &mdash; the <code>emgrip</code> command (from the <code>emdebian-grip</code> package) processes a <code>.deb</code> package from any of the supported Debian architectures, and generates an equivalent Emdebian Grip package.  That way the binaries, maintainer scripts and dependencies of the original Debian packages are untouched, but the overall size and the installation footprint of the packages are reduced.<ref name="lwn-embedian">{{cite web
 | url = https://lwn.net/Articles/327898/
 | title = Emdebian Grip 1.0: The universal embedded operating system
 | date = 2009-04-08 | accessdate = 2013-10-16
 | publisher = [[LWN.net]]
}}</ref>

As the Emdebian Grip packages are not recompiled, they are completely [[binary compatible]] with Debian, so it is even possible to mix Emdebian and Debian packages &mdash; or to even migrate an existing Debian system to Emdebian Grip.<ref name="lwn-embedian" />

